</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ukytherion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kytherion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 334<br> <font color=#E9D756>(12/24/01 10:28:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrfrm18.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=238.topic&index=39>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> mmmkay</span><hr size=1> 1)  Do you feel Clinton was justified in lying about the BJ?<br>
<br>
Yes. I would have.<br>
<br>
<br>
2)  Do you feel that Clinton should have been punished for the actual perjury?  If so, what punishment would have been appropriate and why?<br>
<br>
Not until he was out of office. <br>
<br>
<br>
3)  Do you feel the trial should have waited till he was out of office due to the nature of it?  (Personal)<br>
<br>
See number 2.<br>
<br>
<br>
4)  Do you feel we (as the people and including our congressmen whom we elect to represent us) should never investigate the personal life of the President while he is in office?<br>
<br>
Unless there is compelling evidence for a formal investigation of a capital crime, I feel as though exposing the lives of our leaders is a job for the free press, not Congress. So unless a Secret Service person comes forward with evidence of a pile of bodies, leave it to the tabloids. When Congress begins behaving like the staff of the National Enquirer, it's up to the people to reign them in.<br>
<br>
<br>
5)  Do you feel that it is appropriate for a sitting President to lie, even if he may not get caught in it?<br>
<br>
&quot;Appropriate&quot;? That's a bit half-assed, don't you think?<br>
<br>
I feel it is NECESSARY for the president to lie in the course of his job. I don't have to LIKE it. I'm not sure that appropriateness comes into it at all.<br>
<br>
<br>
6)  Do you feel it is appropriate for a sitting President to lie only about personal issues?<br>
<br>
See number 4. Particularly, if personal issues are being used by political enemies to undermine the authority of the presidency, the president should defend the office by any means necessary, including telling big fat lies.<br>
<br>
<br>
7)  As the president is our Chief Executive officer and is our Ambassador to the World, do you feel that a known liar, such as Clinton, was a good choice (in retrospect)?  Please answer based on his own merits, not in comparisons.<br>
<br>
Any judgement on this would be entirely premature. As the &quot;Ambassador to the World&quot;, he was fairly well-liked, and had a number of successes, mostly in dealing with our closest allies. Since we can only really determine such things by comparison, I'll disregard your instruction and point out that Nixon, despite personal failings, served this country admirably as a diplomat to the world.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Does anyone here feel that the way in which we conduct ourselves in our personal life is usually if not often the way we conduct ourselves in our professional life as well?<br>
<br>
No, because I know history. I know that Julius Caesar was notorious for sleeping with anything that moved and for running up debts with half of Rome. His troops called him &quot;the Whoremaster&quot;. I know that Winston Churchill was an obese alcoholic who was famous for bragging and happily admitted to lying whenever it suited his purposes. His memoirs are chock full of absolute revisionist horseshit.<br>
<br>
I also know that these men rank as two of the finest leaders that Western civilization has ever produced.<br>
<br>
Hitler, on the other hand, was a quiet, pleasant sort who never drank, smoked or ate red meat. If he hadn't been trying to stuff millions of people into gas chambers, he'd have fit right in at the local Baptist church.<br>
<br>
If history supported the conclusion that one's personal habits and conduct indicated one's professional capabilities, it would be an easy task to choose the good from the bad, and the rulers from the subjects.<br>
<br>
But history in no way supports such a conclusion. The world is an ambiguous place, and attempting to impose black and white rules on complex issues leads to a great deal of disappointment.<br>
<br>
See Cendan for details.<br>
<br>
<br>
