<br>
1)	No, lying on the stand is a crime.  We are protected by 5th amendment rights to avoid having to do that.  Clinton got up there and took an oath.  He can answer questions, refuse to answer questions, but lying is not an option.<br>
2)	Yes he should have been punished, the punishment should fit the crime.  He should receive no harder or easier judgment.<br>
3)	I think the trial could have waited.. since most trials are not immediate anyway.  Problem is that he made this nation look bad and removing him (through trial) would have been better.<br>
4)	I don’t think we should know what is going on in the personal life of the president but I also think that events in the oval office are not personal.  It’s a mistake (although a long standing one) to have the office of the president be the home of the president also because it tends to blur the lines.  I worked with my wife for a while and I tried to keep personal stuff at home, and business stuff at the office.<br>
<br>
Although this wasn’t part of the question, I want to point out in the context of what happened… they shouldn’t have asked.. but they did.  He could have said “I plead the 5th because that’s a personal question.”<br>
5)	A lie is a lie… a lie is never not a lie.  To lie is a bad thing.. we aren’t talking morals here we are talking common sense.  To want no one to lie is idealistic, but I think we can all see the benefit in a society where things can be taken at face value.  Its up to you to decide if you are a person who is going to tell the truth in spite of dealing with people who lie to you, or if you are going to be a person who lies because everyone else does.  SO… it is inappropriate for a president to lie, despite the fact that people assume he is going to be lying, God forbid the president becomes an office worthy of respect.<br>
6)	To lie about a personal issue is a cop out.  See above about lying.  You have the right to refuse to answer personal questions.<br>
7)	No Clinton was not a good choice but to be fair, neither were the people he ran against.  <br>
<br>
I don’t understand how people can hold to the opinion that his personal life is his.  That’s like saying an employer can’t ask you if you have ever been convicted of a crime when they hire you.  That’s personal right?  No.  They need to know that because integrity is a part of the job.<br>
<br>
The president is more so because not only is he going to be put in a position where trustworthiness is needed, but he is going to be put in a position where people are going to see if he is not a man of integrity.<br>
 <p><font color=green><b>Cendan Tankenpriest</b></font color><br>
